# **TICKET HANDLING AND CONTENT POLICY (Ubersmith)**

Date: 4/15/2020

In order to ensure consistency on all support tickets, the following steps are required for all support tickets received by a client or created on their behalf. 

1\. When a new ticket is received or created, the following should be checked: 

1. Check to make sure the Client ID is set properly on the ticket.  
2. Ensure that the sending email address is valid and associated with the person requesting support.  
3. If the sender of the ticket cannot be properly verified, kindly advise the client to resend the request using an authorized contact on their account.  
4. Please note, an automated  initial acknowledgement to the client indicating that we have received their request is sent in response to all incoming tickets.

2\. A follow up to the client is sent notifying them that work is starting on their request.

1. If remote access to their computer is needed, send a follow up requesting permission to access their machine.

3\. If a resolution cannot be reached within an initial period of time, request assistance from peers or the department directly above yours.

1. Keep in mind that it is ok to reschedule a time to further assist the client if research time is needed.

4\. Record detailed notes  on the ticket as each update is posted, outlining the steps taken during the remediation process.

1. If appropriate, detailed steps should be provided as public updates visible by the client.  
2. Additional private comments should be included on the ticket if internal discussion, research or other information was gathered to resolve the ticket.  
3. Each follow up and comment requires “time spent” to be recorded.  
   

5\. Once the ticket has been resolved, a final summary of the steps taken and resolution needs to be provided as a public follow up to the client. 

1. This update should clearly communicate to the client that the ticket has been completed and is now considered fully resolved.  
2. This step also provides useful information to our team for future reference.

6\. Determine if the ticket can be "Closed" or if it should be passed to the Controller department using the following guide: [Billable Ticket Reporting Policy](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1XGJL0HUcSHqgstyY5xBpodLZ2jpLbBKXONnWIAwOmXY/edit#heading=h.wrpb31oxmp3g). 

7\. The ticket is now complete and can be considered fully processed.

8\. Additional guidelines.

1. The ultimate goal for all tickets is to reach a resolution in a timely manner, and for all billable items to be accurately recorded.  
2. Every effort should be made to reach out to the client in order to get movement on every ticket. This is usually achieved via email and or phone call.  
3. Unless otherwise noted, every ticket should be updated at least once per shift in an effort to keep movement going on the ticket. It should be a very rare case for any ticket to sit more than 24 hours without an update from our support staff.  
4. Communications with clients need to be free of grammatical errors, concise, and maintain a professional nature.  
5. When applicable, a pre-existing template needs to be used over a manual follow up to maintain standardization and consistency in our responses.  
6. Any ticket placed on hold should have a timer applied for the ticket to open back up at the appropriate time.  
7. Communication is key\! If a client does not reply in a timely manner to a ticket follow up, a call to them should be made if possible.  
8. Work with your team\!  
9. Refrain from promising strict ETAs. Even if 100% sure, make preparations to add extra time to any expected resolution deadlines to accommodate unforeseen difficulties.  
10. Passwords should never be sent in plain text through the ticketing system. Always use SendSafely to protect sensitive information such as passwords.
